index 0000000..cda4b2e
--- /dev/null
+++ b/CLAUDE.md
@@ -0,0 +1,66 @@
+# Project Guidelines
+
+## Architecture
+- This project follows the repository pattern for data access
+- Services depend on repositories, never on each other directly
+- All inter-service communication uses the EventBus (see ADR below)
+- All business logic lives in the service layer
+
+## Coding Conventions
+- Use TypeScript strict mode — no `any` types
+- All public methods must have JSDoc comments
+- Use dependency injection via constructor parameters
+- Error handling: throw typed errors, never return null for errors
+- Prefer async/await over raw Promises
+
+## Testing
+- Tests use vitest
+- Each module has a corresponding test file in tests/
+- Mock external dependencies, test business logic directly
+- Minimum: test the happy path and one error path per public method
+
+## File Organization
+- src/models/ — Data models and interfaces
+- src/repositories/ — Data access layer (implements repository interfaces)
+- src/services/ — Business logic layer
+- src/events/ — Event definitions and event bus
+- src/utils/ — Shared utilities (database, logger, pagination)
+- src/config/ — Configuration files
+- tests/ — Test files mirroring src/ structure
+
+## ADR: Unified EventBus for Inter-Service Communication
+
+**Decision:** All inter-service communication (including notifications) uses the
+EventBus pattern exclusively. The CallbackRegistry pattern is NOT used for
+notification triggers.
+
+**Context:** The codebase previously used two patterns:
+1. EventBus (`src/events/event-bus.ts`) — for `order:created` events
+2. CallbackRegistry (`src/utils/callback-registry.ts`) — for `order:status-changed` events
+
+This inconsistency forced developers to learn two patterns and made it unclear
+which to use for new features.
+
+**Why EventBus over CallbackRegistry:**
+- **Async support:** EventBus handlers can be async, which real notification
+  delivery (email, SMS) requires. CallbackRegistry is synchronous only.
+- **Event log:** EventBus records all emitted events, enabling debugging, replay,
+  and audit trails. CallbackRegistry has no history.
+- **Type safety:** The `AppEvent` union in `event-types.ts` provides a single
+  source of truth for all event shapes. CallbackRegistry requires separate type
+  parameters per instance.
+- **Loose coupling:** Services only depend on EventBus (injected via constructor),
+  not on shared global singletons. CallbackRegistry used a module-level export
+  (`statusChangeCallbacks`) creating implicit coupling.
+- **Extensibility:** Adding a new listener (e.g., analytics) means subscribing to
+  EventBus — no changes to the emitting service.
+
+**When to use CallbackRegistry:** The `CallbackRegistry` class still exists in
+`src/utils/callback-registry.ts` as a general-purpose utility. It is appropriate
+for lightweight, intra-module callbacks (e.g., UI event handlers) where the
+EventBus overhead is unnecessary. Do NOT use it for cross-service communication.
+
+## Git Practices
+- Commit atomically per logical change
+- Write descriptive commit messages explaining the "why"
+- Run tests before committing
